<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B22FB4FB60FA09" blockId="7.[174,1233,1476,1855]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
T y p e s p e c i e s: 
<materialsCitation id="3B113CFCD176FFC469952FB5FB60FA09" ID-GBIF-Occurrence="3751756303" country="Belgium" location="Antwerp area" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" specimenCount="1" typeStatus="holotype">
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D176FFC469952FB5FC6AFA28" authority="Van Beneden, 1877" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[452,941,1476,1503]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<originalDetermination id="A8678E5DD176FFC469952FB5FC6AFA28" box="[452,941,1476,1503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D176FFC469952FB5FD6AFA29" box="[452,685,1476,1502]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Platyphoca vulgaris</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC46AEB2FB4FC6AFA28" author="Van Beneden, P. J." box="[698,941,1476,1503]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="1 - 88" refId="ref10746" refString="Van Beneden, P. J. Description des ossements fossiles des environs d'Anvers, 1. Pinnipedes ou amphitheriens // Musee Royal d'Histoire Naturelle de Belgique, Annales. - 1877. - 1. - P. 1 - 88." type="book chapter" year="1877">Van Beneden, 1877</bibRefCitation>
</originalDetermination>
</taxonomicName>
, by original monotypy. 
<typeStatus id="54C28803D176FFC468FF2F95FEDBFA09" box="[174,284,1508,1534]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Holotype</typeStatus>
from 
<geologicalTimeScale id="F959B60AD176FFC469352F95FD80FA09" box="[356,583,1508,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">middle (?) Pliocene</geologicalTimeScale>
(Scaldisian) deposits in the 
<location id="8EA6607AD176FFC46BC12F94FBF5FA08" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03D087B7D176FFCB68FF2E9BFD67FBAB:8EA6607AD176FFC46BC12F94FBF5FA08" box="[912,1074,1509,1535]" country="Belgium" name="Antwerp area" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Antwerp area</location>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46C6C2F95FB64FA09" box="[1085,1187,1508,1534]" name="Belgium" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Belgium</collectingCountry>
.
</materialsCitation>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B22C74FCE2F989" blockId="7.[174,1233,1476,1855]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
S t r a t i g r a p h i c a l r a n g e. The 
<typeStatus id="54C28803D176FFC46A262C74FD6EF9E8" box="[631,681,1541,1567]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">type</typeStatus>
species is also known from the 
<location id="8EA6607AD176FFC46C762C75FB4CF9E9" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03D087B7D176FFCB68FF2E9BFD67FBAB:8EA6607AD176FFC46C762C75FB4CF9E9" box="[1063,1163,1540,1566]" country="United States of America" municipality="Yorktown Formation" name="Pliocene" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Pliocene</location>
(5.0– 5.8 ma) 
<collectingMunicipality id="6BA2ACDBD176FFC469452C55FDD4F9C9" box="[276,531,1572,1598]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Yorktown Formation</collectingMunicipality>
of the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46A9C2C55FCB7F9C8" box="[717,880,1572,1599]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">United States</collectingCountry>
. Herein, we introduce a new species from the late Miocene (early-middle Tortonian, 8.0–11.5 ma) 
<location id="8EA6607AD176FFC46BB72C34FF34F988" LSID="urn:lsid:plazi:treatment:03D087B7D176FFCB68FF2E9BFD67FBAB:8EA6607AD176FFC46BB72C34FF34F988" country="Denmark" name="Gram Formation of Gram" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Gram Formation of Gram</location>
and Skaerum MØlle, Jutland, western 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46AFC2C15FCE6F989" box="[685,801,1636,1662]" name="Denmark" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Denmark</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFC468B22CF4FD46F928" blockId="7.[174,1233,1476,1855]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">
R e f e r r e d m a t e r i a l. Humeri, 2nd phalanx, innominata, metatarsal IV, tibia, and humeri from the Antwerp area, 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46A642CD5FD5DF949" box="[565,666,1700,1726]" name="Belgium" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Belgium</collectingCountry>
, from western 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC46B002CD5FC03F949" box="[849,964,1700,1726]" name="Denmark" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">Denmark</collectingCountry>
, and from the eastern 
<collectingCountry id="F36E7631D176FFC468FF2CB5FE8CF928" box="[174,331,1732,1759]" name="United States of America" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">United States</collectingCountry>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D176FFC469D72CB5FDB3F928" author="Koretsky, I. A. &amp; Ray, C. E." box="[390,628,1732,1759]" pageId="7" pageNumber="426" pagination="81 - 140" refId="ref9574" refString="Koretsky, I. A., Ray, C. E. Phocidae of the Pliocene of eastern USA // Geology and paleontology of the Lee Creek Mine, North Carolina IV / Eds C. E. Ray, D. A. Bohaska, I. A. Koretsky et al. - Virginia Museum of Natural History, 2008. - 15 (Special Publication). - P. 81 - 140." type="book chapter" year="2008">Koretsky, Ray, 2008</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC636A1D176FFCB68B22C94FBEFFCCC" blockId="7.[174,1233,1476,1855]" lastBlockId="8.[166,1225,769,1116]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="427" pageId="7" pageNumber="426">E m e n d e d d i a g n o s i s. Deltoid crest of humerus very short and terminating at less than 1/2 of length of bone; from base of lesser tubercle, along medial surface of bone, passes a crest that is only slightly shorter than deltoid crest; maximal enlargement of deltoid crest in its proximal part; intertubercular groove very shallow and not well defined; both epicondyles well developed and very wide; distal part of each epicondyle flat.</paragraph>
