<paragraph id="8BC636A1D179FFCB688A2933FD67FBAB" blockId="8.[166,1225,769,1116]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">
D i s c u s s i o n. 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB69C72930FDBCFCAC" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[406,635,833,859]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB69C72930FDBCFCAC" box="[406,635,833,859]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Platyphoca vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(pl. 3, 
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6A842930FCE3FCAC" box="[725,804,833,859]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">1A–1B</emphasis>
) was originally mentioned by 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D179FFCB6CC62933FEBDFC8B" author="Van Beneden, P. J." pageId="8" pageNumber="427" pagination="783 - 802" refId="ref10666" refString="Van Beneden, P. J. Les phoques fossiles du bassin d'Anvers // Bulletins de l'Academie Royale des Sciences, des Lettres et des Beaux-Arts de Belgique - 1876 a. - 41. - P. 783 - 802." type="book chapter" year="1876">Van Beneden (1876 a)</bibRefCitation>
, who considered it to be very close to the Recent 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB6B822910FB05FC8C" baseAuthorityName="Erxleben" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[979,1218,865,891]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Erignathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="barbatus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6B822910FB05FC8C" box="[979,1218,865,891]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Erignathus barbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The size of the humerus approaches that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB6AF129F0FCD8FC6C" authorityName="Gill" authorityYear="1866" box="[672,799,897,923]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Erignathus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6AF129F0FCD8FC6C" box="[672,799,897,923]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Erignathus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
more closely than any other phocid. This poorly known, obscure, but distinctive species was described on the basis of only a few bones of the postcranial skeleton. 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB6A3D29B3FD21FC2C" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[620,742,961,987]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6A3D29B3FD21FC2C" box="[620,742,961,987]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">P. vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was a very large animal, perhaps similar in size to the modern species 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB69AF2990FD18FC0C" baseAuthorityName="Erxleben" baseAuthorityYear="1777" box="[510,735,993,1019]" class="Phaeophyceae" family="Sargassaceae" genus="Cystophora" kingdom="Chromista" order="Fucales" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Ochrophyta" rank="species" species="cristata">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB69AF2990FD18FC0C" box="[510,735,993,1019]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Cystophora cristata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This intriguing species has been virtually ignored in the literature except for a few comprehensive works, where 
<taxonomicName id="4C794D22D179FFCB6BB72E70FB0FFBEC" authorityName="Van Beneden" authorityYear="1877" box="[998,1224,1025,1051]" class="Mammalia" family="Phocidae" genus="Platyphoca" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="vulgaris">
<emphasis id="B90DEAB3D179FFCB6BB72E70FB0FFBEC" box="[998,1224,1025,1051]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="427">Platyphoca vulgaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is listed among species from the Pliocene of Europe (e. g. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D179FFCB6B012E53FBD0FBCC" author="Trouessart, E. L." box="[848,1047,1057,1084]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" refId="ref10619" refString="Trouessart, E. L. Catalogus mammalium tam viventium quam fossilium. Quinquennale supplementum anno 1904, 1. Primates, Prosimiae, Chiroptera, Insectivora, Carnivora, Pinnipedia. - Berolini: R. Friedlander and Sohn, 1904. - 288 p." type="book" year="1904">Trouessart, 1904</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D179FFCB6C732E50FB02FBCC" author="Kellogg, R." box="[1058,1221,1057,1083]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" pagination="23 - 132" refId="ref8984" refString="Kellogg, R. Pinnipeds from Miocene and Pleistocene deposits of California // University of California Publications, Bulletin of the Department of Geological Sciences. - 1922. - 13. - P. 23 - 132." type="book chapter" year="1922">Kellogg, 1922</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFE84B50D179FFCB68F72E30FE91FBAB" author="Simpson, G. G." box="[166,342,1089,1116]" pageId="8" pageNumber="427" pagination="1 - 350" refId="ref10441" refString="Simpson, G. G. The principles of classification and a classification of mammals // Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History. - 1945. - 85. - P. 1 - 350." type="book chapter" year="1945">Simpson, 1945</bibRefCitation>
; 
